  <!--<div style="text-align: center">-->
  <!--<img src="/assets/cadu/images/content/sectorial2.png" alt="" style="width: 80%"/>-->
  <!--</div>-->
  <p>According to revised figures from INEGI, GDP of the construction sector for full-year 2018 expanded by 0.6%, partially
    reflecting the usual industry slowdown explained by the start of  the new federal administration. However,
    according to the Construction Sector’s Economic Resarch Centre ( Centro de Estudios Económicos del Sector
    de la Construcción - CEESCO), the sector GDP growth for 2019 is expected to be between the range of 2.0% and
    2.5%, mainly driven by private investment. This, coupled with the potential rise in Mexican Federal Institute for Worker’s Housing
    (Instituto del Fondo Nacional de la Vivienda para los Trabajadores – Infonavit) mortgage credit cap* , will
    contribute to a greater number of homes sold during the year.</p>

  <p>Construction input prices increased 10.3% YoY in 2018, attributed by the entry into force of certain foreign
    policies such as the imposition of duties on Mexican steel and aluminum by the United States. However, in
    January, this trend has shown signs of improving, ending at 8.6% YoY, highlighting the decrease in key input
    prices such as asphalt, rod, wire and wire rod.</p>


